[normal]The National Children’s Bureau (NCB)[bold] 
[normal]The National Children’s Bureau (NCB) is a leading research and development charity that for 50 years has been working to improve the experiences and life chances of children and young people across England and Northern Ireland, especially the most vulnerab
[normal]le. 
[normal]We play a strategic support and leadership role across the sector by:
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]initiating partnerships and projects, for example, [ children's play, disability, life skills, and youth justice that aim to improve the lives of children and young people]
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]sust
[normal]aining the effectiveness and efficiency of over 30 key specialist networks, including the Council for Disabled Children, the Every Disabled Child Matters campaign, the Early Childhood Forum, Anti-Bullying Alliance, Play England and the Childhood Bereavemen
[normal]t Network 
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]championing the use of evidence, and the involvement of children and young people, to shape and improve national policy and local services 
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]building the skills, knowledge and networks of front-line practitioners and voluntary groups working 
[normal]with children and young people
[normal]Every year we reach more than 100,000 children and young peopl
[normal]e through our links with 
[normal]organis
[normal]ations
[normal] including local authorities, children’s service providers, academic bodies, schools and voluntary 
[normal]organisations
[normal]. 
[normal]The Council for Disabled Children[bold]The Council for Disabled Children (CDC) is the umbrella body for the disabled children's sector in England, with links to other UK nations. 
[normal]Hosted by NCB, we are the only national body that brings together the diverse range of 
[normal]organisations
[normal] that work with and for disabled children to support the development and implementation of policy and practice.  Our work impacts on over 800,000 disabled c
[normal]hildren and their families.
